Here we load the main checkpoint, and then the LORAs

Make sure to check the nodes where you need models. Sometimes you get lucky, and you have the exact same model used in this saved file but often times you will have different models or models named differently.
Optional Motion LoRAs to give the image/camera some movement.

Here we take all the basic inputs of the sampler and put them in a "pipe" so that it is more easily wired to the destination without a big mess. Later we will use the FromBasicPipe to retrieve these values.
AnimateDiff does the actual animation and sets things up for video.
Initialize variables for the frame rate, frame cap/length, seed, and Source Video.
Controller for enabling and disabling different groups. Useful for disabling different controlnets if we don't need them, and for disabling the post processing and upscaling if we want quick tests.

IP Adapter / Style Reference.

Use the Load Image to input an image to guide the style.

Load in the IP Adapter Plus Model, and the appropriate CLIP Vision.

Can play with sharpening on the Prep Image for ClipVision if results are not very sharp.

Inside the IPAdapter Advanced, play with the WEIGHT and WEIGHT TYPE to dial in the amount of influence of the style.

widgets_values: Depth is ControlNet that gets the depth map of the image to determine where things might exist in 3d space in the image.
Canny is a ControlNet that uses Edge Detection to get an outline of the objects in the video.
Softedge is a ControlNet that uses edge detection to get a soft edge outline of the main parts of the image.
OpenPose is a ControlNet that uses joint tracking to get a digital skeleton of a human and map the resulting image to this.
LineArt is a ControlNet that extracts the dominant outlines in the image.
Apply the ControlNet model, and here we control the overall strength of all the ControlNets

Run our first sampler from all the frames, with the conditioning we added with the ControlNets.

We can mess with the values on the KSampler to get different nuanced looks. (default: steps 20, CFG 4, euler-ancestral)

This really improves your image; however, it takes very long to run each step. 

In the iterative upscaler you could run 1 step for shorter render times but, if possible, run more steps for improved quality, you will see a big difference. You could also skip this part by bypassing the nodes in this section and it will go straight to the face detailer.

Post Processing for a cleaner and smoother video output.

1. VFI (Video Frame Interpolation) - smoothes out the video
2. FaceRestore - restores faces as much as possible
3. Upscale - uses another upscaler here to upscale the image.
